In recent years, the timepiece industry has been forced to dramatically rethink how it markets to women.
Here are some of watch aficionado Charlie Boyd's (@twinklefingersboyd) top picks from the 2026 fair, which show that these days, a "ladies" watch is in the eye of the beholder.
@bvlgari, Octo Finissimo 37 – flaunting the same architecturally-inspired curves, edges and corners that emulate Bulgari's home city of Rome, this featherlight piece comes crafted in either titanium or 18-karat yellow gold, with three-day power reserve.
@cartier, Baignoire – the 2026 edition of the Biagnoire has been toughened up with chic prickles — with one of the two versions created from up-turned diamonds.
@vancleefarpels, Heure d'Ici & Heure d'Ailleurs –  the newly unveiled Heure d'Ici & Heure d'Ailleurs is minimal, though none the less elegant. Priced at $48,000 — the perfectly sized 38mm watch boasts a cognac-hued enamel dial that evokes @chanelofficials's cult Rouge Noir shade of nail polish.
@rolex, Oyster Perpetual Day-Date 40 – Rolex hasn't just unveiled a new iteration of one of its best-loved timepieces for 2026, but has crafted it in a whole new precious metal alloy. Called Jubilee Gold, the watch was conceived and developed in the maison's Swiss workshop and part of a batch of new releases coinciding with the 100th anniversary celebration of the groundbreaking Oyster model.
@marli New York, MARLI Timepieces L35 – MARLI New York has presented its first foray into watchmaking with a collection that was five years in the making. Meticulously carving mother-of-pearl on five different axis, each dial is a series of iridescent, perfectly polished pyramids, amplifying the shine of each 18-karat rose-gold or titanium case, available with or without diamonds upon the bezel.
📸 : Fabrice Coffrini/AFP/Getty Images/Bvlgari/Cartier/Van Cleef & Arpels/Rolex/Marli

AI 🤖 COULD NEVER!!
I don’t think there has been another successful brand × photographer collaboration since Ganjam high jewelry and Prabuddha Dasgupta, which was so monumental and ahead of its time because it defied all kinds of logic. They set the tone for what jewelry ads and jewelry photography could look like. Prabuddha’s visual language was so distinct and so strict, and he did exactly what he wanted, always photographing on his own terms.
For Ganjam to be such a big brand at the time and still allow that kind of raw, almost nerve-wracking, anti-manicured photography is what made it so powerful. That approach has since become the crux of how so many photographers work and how India is visually represented (and how western photographers come and shoot India at large 👀☕️). He did it effortlessly, for years and years in a way that truly hasn’t been matched since.
@saviojon clothes
@suzcapmer did the styling
Hair & make up @deepa.verma.makeup

